05196nam a22007455i 9780226593722DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192018ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018020252  a97802265937227 a10.7208/97802265937222doi  a(DE-B1597)523891  a(OCoLC)1078553489  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aPN1993.5.C8bF44 2019 4aPN1993.5.C8bF44 2019 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a791.43072912231 aFeeney, Megan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHollywood in Havana :bUS Cinema and Revolutionary Nationalism in Cuba before 1959 /cMegan Feeney. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2019] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b31 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Looking Up: Hollywood and Revolutionary Cuban Nationalism -- t1. The Film Business That Unites: Early US Cinema in Havana, 1897–1928 -- t2. Teaching Eyes to See: The Advent of Cuban Film Criticism, 1928–1934 -- t3. Our Men in Havana: Hollywood and Good Neighborly Bonds, 1934–1941 -- t4. You Are Men! Fight for Liberty! Hollywood Heroes and the Pan-American Bonds of World War II -- t5. Breaking the Chains: Hollywood Noir in Postwar Havana, 1946–1952 -- t6. Rebel Idealism: Hollywood in Havana during the Batistato, 1952–1958 -- tEpilogue. The Show Goes On: Hollywood in Havana after 1958 -- tAbbreviations of Frequently Cited Sources -- tNotes -- tIndex of Films -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom the turn of the twentieth century through the late 1950s, Havana was a locus for American movie stars, with glamorous visitors including Errol Flynn, John Wayne, and Marlon Brando. In fact, Hollywood was seemingly everywhere in pre-Castro Havana, with movie theaters three to a block in places, widely circulated silver screen fanzines, and terms like “cowboy” and “gangster” entering Cuban vernacular speech. Hollywood in Havana uses this historical backdrop as the catalyst for a startling question: Did exposure to half a century of Hollywood pave the way for the Cuban Revolution of 1959? Megan Feeney argues that the freedom fighting extolled in American World War II dramas and the rebellious values and behaviors seen in postwar film noir helped condition Cuban audiences to expect and even demand purer forms of Cuban democracy and national sovereignty. At the same time, influential Cuban intellectuals worked to translate Hollywood ethics into revolutionary rhetoric—which, ironically, led to pointed critiques and subversions of the US presence in Cuba. Hollywood in Havana not only expands our notions of how American cinema was internalized around the world—it also broadens our view of the ongoing history of US-Cuban interactions, both cultural and political.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aMotion pictures, AmericanzCubaxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion pictures, AmericanzCubaxInfluence. 0aNational liberation movementszCuba. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aHollywood abroad.  aRepublican Cuba.  aUS imperialism.  aUS-Cuban relations.  afilm business.  afilm criticism.  afilm reception.  amasculinity.  arevolutionary nationalism.  atransnational.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishz978311061017808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019z9783110606195oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicag